nd poetry itself as a form ideally suited to crafting a relational self, offer us new ways of thinking about selfhood today—and a resource for reimagining both secular and religious ways of being in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAuthorship in literature. 0aChristian poetry, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aDevotional poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aInterpersonal relations in literature. 0aLove in literature. 0aMarriage in literature. 0aProtestant poetry, EnglishyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aReformationzEngland. 0aSelf in literature. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aAnne Bradstreet.  aEnglish Reformation.  aGeorge Herbert.  aHannah Arendt.  aJohn Donne.  aJudith Butler.  apoetry.  arelationality.  asubjectivity.  atheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022643415540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226434292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226434292/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles